  "text": "T HIS work is a contribution to motion compensation in dynamic tomography [CITATION_1] . These last years, several studies have been dedicated to this subject, mainly for cardiac imaging but also for patient motion compensation [CITATION_2] , [CITATION_3] . Indeed, reconstructions of moving organs suffer from artifacts. Gating methods [CITATION_4] - [CITATION_5] have been proposed to improve cardiac imaging. Computed tomography (CT) scanner rotation speed and sampling parameter adjustment to the heart period were also suggested in order to improve the reconstructed images [CITATION_6] . This paper shares the same approach as Crawford et al. [CITATION_7] and Roux et al. [CITATION_8] . The idea is to introduce a time (denoted by ) dependent motion or a deformation model within the reconstruction.",
